<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-b9_jdXY1tDTzmsCXTWPh7Q" name=",__Vmq8J6WEeCHFd5_MqJHKQ" guid="-b9_jdXY1tDTzmsCXTWPh7Q" changeDate="2011-08-24T05:00:47.146-0700" version="7.5.1">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Two methods are available to analyze the risk of random HW failures, the first using probabilistic metrics (i.e.&#xD;
    quantified FTA) and the second being the individual evaluation of every residual, single and dual point failure that&#xD;
    can lead to a violation of a safety goal.This second form of analysis is can also be considered to be a cut set&#xD;
    analysis.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For details of the first method refer ISO 26262, volume 5, clause 9.4.3 and for the second clause 9.4.4&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is required that item only needs to comply with the results of one of these assessments&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is highly recommended that the user refers to ISO 26262, volume 5, clause 9.4 for the detailed advice and guidance&#xD;
    required to achieve this goal.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is recommended that users refer to ISO 26262, volume 5 annex&amp;nbsp;D for evaluation of the diagnostic coverage.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Quantified FTA can be used in both methods see, &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../practice.tech.real_time.safe_rel_analysis.base-ibm/guidances/practices/safe_rel_an_966E315A.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_2BtTQLePEd-05egMquN4Dg&quot;>Safety and Reliability Analysis&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <purpose>To determine the effects of random hardware failures on the functional safety of the item being developed.</purpose>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription>
